    "Property_Analysis": "LogD (Distribution coefficient at a specific pH, typically 7.4) reflects the compound's lipophilicity and distribution between an organic (octanol) and aqueous phase. Higher LogD indicates greater lipophilicity. Polar and ionizable groups tend to decrease LogD by increasing affinity for the aqueous phase.",
    "Limitation_in_Source_Molecule_for_Property": "The source molecule possesses multiple polar functional groups contributing to low LogD: the phenolic hydroxyl group (ionizable, H-bond donor/acceptor), the hydroxymethyl group (polar, H-bond donor/acceptor), and the polar hydantoin ring itself (amide N-H donors, carbonyl acceptors). The phenolic OH, in particular, can ionize at physiological pH, significantly increasing water solubility and lowering LogD.",
    "Optimization_for_Source_Molecule": "To increase LogD, polarity and ionizability should be reduced. A viable strategy involves: 1) Masking the acidic phenolic hydroxyl group, for example, by converting it to a methyl ether (-OCH3). This eliminates the acidic proton and increases lipophilicity. 2) Replacing the polar hydroxymethyl group (-CH2OH) on the hydantoin nitrogen with a less polar, more lipophilic group, such as a methyl group (-CH3). This removes a hydrogen bond donor/acceptor site.",
    "Final_Target_Molecule": "O=C1NC(Cc2ccc(OC)cc2)C(=O)N(C)C1"
  }
]

